Eduardo Abela letter to José María Chacón y Calvo, October 29, 1934		Abela, Eduardo		In this letter Eduardo Abela congratulates José María Chacón y Calvo on his appointment as Cuba's Director of Culture. Abela informs his friend of his desire to participate in a competition organized by the agency Chacón y Calvo directs to purchase works by Cuban artists which will form part of the permanent collection of the museum in Havana. Abela also mentions that the Secretary of Education, Jorge Mañach, asked him to purchase copies of classic art works in Italy and his need to obtain the appropriate funds to be able to carry on this assignment. Luis Estévez y Romero and his wife Marta Abreu de Estévez letter to Tomás Estrada Palma, December 31, 1907		Estévez y Romero, Luis, 1846-1909; Abreu y Arencibia, Marta, 1845-1909		In this letter Luis Estévez wishes Tomás Estrada Palma health and well-being for the new year. Estévez also mentions to his friend his preoccupation and pessimism about the morale in Cuba. His wife, Marta Abreu, a philanthropist and eminent citizen born in Santa Clara, Cuba, also writes a few lines to Estrada Palma and family wishing them success for the coming year. Francisco Arredondo Morando letter to José Germán Miret, October 18, 1957		Arredondo Morando, Francisco		In this letter Francisco Arredondo Morando, mayor of Camagüey, writes to José Germán Miret, director of the Abraham Lincoln Library in Havana, Cuba. Arredondo tells Miret that he is gladly sending the patriotic books "Arpas y Clarines" and "El Lugareño y Otros Próceres", published by his office, so that they will become part of the holdings of the Abraham Lincoln Library.	Letterhead: "República de Cuba, Alcaldía Municipal de Camagüey [Camagüey's coat of arms]" appears at the top left of the first page. Embossed: "Alcaldía Municipal de Camagüey." Will of Amalia Simoni y Argilagos, June 17, 1892		Simoni y Argilagos, Amalia		Original manuscript of the last will and testament of Amalia Simoni y Argilagos, wife of general Ignacio Agramonte y Loynaz. In this document she names her two children, Ignacio Agramonte y Simoni and Herminia Agramonte y Simoni, as her universal inheritors. The document is witnessed and signed by Enrique V. Agramonte, José Jacinto Luis, and Benjamín J. Guerra and it is notarized by José G. Morales. F. N. Acosta letter to the G. W. Van Vleck Co., September 3, 1907		Acosta, F. N.		F. N. Acosta writes to the G.W. Van Vleck Co. after following a treatment for piles and fistulas, and using their medication for six months. He highly recommends this treatment and points out that prior to using this medication doctors wanted to operate on him after eleven months of suffering from this condition. Miguel de Aldama letter to José González Curbelo, Junio 19, 1874		Aldama, Miguel de		In this letter Miguel de Aldama, from New York, writes to José González Curbelo. He explains that there is not much he can do about the abuses committed by Emilia Casanova de Villaverde, among others, that have a detriment effect to Cuba's independence efforts. He goes on to say that this behavior will continue so long as they keep receiving support from people with candid intentions. Miguel de Aldama letter to José González Curbelo, June 20, 1876		Aldama, Miguel de		Letter from Miguel de Aldama, New York, to José González Curbelo, Philadelphia, to whom he refers to as an agent of the Republic of Cuba. He writes in reply to González Curbelo's question on how to execute the Cuban government decree regarding the registration of Cuban citizens residing abroad, as well as non-Cuban citizens that were sympathizers of the Cuban revolution. Aldama also appeals to the friends of an independent Cuba for their support and donations to help the troops fighting for the cause. Ignacio Agramonte y Loynaz letter to his wife Amalia Simoni y Argilagos, April 18, 1870		Agramonte y Loynaz, Ignacio, 1841-1873		In this letter General Ignacio Agramonte y Loynaz gives his wife news from the front line and tells her how much he misses her. He recounts the engagement that took place when his troops decided to charge against a non-moving Spanish company. The engagement that lasted several hours ended in the defeat of the Spanish company which gained his troops 170 weapons and 6 horses. Agramonte's troops only suffered 5 deaths and 3 wounded, he being amongst the wounded. He tells his wife that his wound is not as deep as the one his heart suffers from being far away from her.		Agramonte y Loynaz, Ignacio, 1841-1873; Simoni y Argilagos, Amalia; Generals -- Cuba -- Correspondence	Manuscripts; Correspondence		1870-04-18	1870-1880	Cuba	1 letter, 2 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Major General Pedro E. Betancourt letter to Patria Tió de Sánchez de Fuentes, January 21, 1930		Betancourt y Dávalos, Pedro Estanislao, 1858-1933		In this letter Mayor General Pedro E. Betancourt, president of the National Council of Veterans, in the name of all the veterans thanks Patria Tió de Sánchez de Fuentes, daughter of Lola Rodríguez de Tió, eminent poet born in Puerto Rico, the three poems of her mother: A Cuba, 10 de Octubre, and 24 de Febrero, that she sent to him as a gift. Betancourt says that Cubans consider her mother a compatriot and also mentions that he had the good fortune of being her mother's friend. Finally he reiterates to Patria Tió his eternal gratitude for so precious legacy.	Letterhead: "[Cuba's coat of arms] Major Gral. Pedro E. Betancourt. Presidente del Consejo Nacional de Veteranos. Primera y C. Vedado-Habana" appears at the top left of the first page.	Betancourt y Dávalos, Pedro Estanislao, 1858-1933; Tió de Sánchez de Fuentes, Patria, 1866-1943; Rodríguez de Tió, Lola, 1843-1924 -- Poetry; Generals -- Cuba -- Correspondence	Manuscripts; Correspondence		1930-01-21	1930-1940	Vedado (Havana, Cuba)	1 letter, 4 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Tomás Estrada Palma letter to Teodoro Pérez Tamayo, October 10, 1906		Estrada Palma, Tomás, 1835-1908		Unsigned letter dated in Matanzas, from Tomás Estrada Palma where he tells Teodoro Pérez Tamayo that in the middle of the social and political imbalance prevailing in Cuba it is comforting to receive a testimony of approval and friendship from him. He comments that everything he has done has been for his love to the homeland. He adds  that when the insurrection took alarming proportions he decided to resign from the presidency but not without warning the United States. He did this in accord with the right that was given to the US by the Platt amendment of intervening in the island. He ends up by saying that a political dependency is preferable to an independent republic destroyed by periodic civil wars.		Estrada Palma, Tomás, 1835-1908; Pérez Tamayo, Teodoro; Platt amendment	Manuscripts; Correspondence		1906-10-10	1900-1910	Matanzas (Cuba)	1 letter, 6 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Tomás Estrada Palma letter to Alberta Gavin, December 28, 1904		Estrada Palma, Tomás, 1835-1908		In this letter Tomás Estrada Palma, president of Cuba, informs Alberta Gavin that he is sending her, under a separate cover, an autographed copy of "International Documents relating to the recognition of the Republic of Cuba". He also sends Miss Gavin his best wishes for the coming year. Alberta Gavin, showing her support of the Cuban cause, presented general Máximo Gómez two Cuban silken flags during the war with Spain. The envelope is also included. Document related to the transfer of the remains of Luis Lorenzo de Clouet y Pietre, count of Fernandina, September 27, 1958		Municipal Administration of Cienfuegos		Document stating that in the Municipal Palace of Cienfuegos on September 27, 1958 the municipal treasurer Ricardo Ríos Collazo delivered a wooden coffer of chestnut-tree containing the remains of Luis Lorenzo de Clouet y Pietre, Spanish brigadier, count of Fernandina and founder of Cienfuegos, to three representatives of the Cienfuegos Atheneum. Moments later the remains were taken to the building of the Trust Company of Cuba to be deposited in a vault of the bank until the monument to the brigadier, where his ashes will be placed, is ready. The document was signed by: Ricardo Ríos Collazo, municipal treasurer; José A. Vidal Fleytes, treasurer of the Atheneum; Florentino Morales Hernández, vicepresident of the Atheneum; Bienvenido Rumbaut Yanes, president of the Atheneum; and Ricardo Rumbaut Yanes, administrator of The Trust Company of Cuba	Letterhead: "[Cienfuegos' coat of arms] Administración Municipal de Cienfuegos. Oficial" appears at the top center. There are two stamp marks, on pages 1 and 3. General Máximo Gómez letter to Pedro Biscay, January 20, 1896		Gómez, Máximo, 1836-1905		In this letter General Máximo Gómez tells Pedro Biscay that he is sending to his care the horse that he personally used throughout the Camagüey military campaign. He mentions that once the wounded horse recovers the letter will prevent army personnel from repossessing it. There is another letter attached (page 2) where General Máximo Gómez writes to the Liberator Army informing them that Pedro Biscay is to be treated with all due respect for showing an honorable neutral conduct during the war. Letter from Pedro Sueyras, representing The Manchester Assurance Company in Cuba, to George S.A. Young, president of the American Fire Insurance Company, New York. Pedro Sueyras says that enclosed with the letter is a slip with information regarding the new law of the Military Governor of Cuba. She mentions she has a large family and that her husband is sick and unemployed. She also points out her husband's abilities and asks for a recommendation for him to work in an office or as an inspector. She adds that she is confident in General Gómez's generosity and that she is thankful for any aid he could send. General Antonio Maceo letter to general Máximo Gómez, June, 1886		Maceo, Antonio, 1845-1896		Letter from Antonio Maceo to General Máximo Gómez asking for authorization to take immediately an expedition to Cuba to aid general Flor Crombet and his troops who were in danger of falling under enemy attack. José Martí and Máximo Gómez document addressed to the chiefs and officers of Jiguaní, May 12, 1895		Martí, José, 1853-1895; Gómez, Máximo, 1836-1905		Document signed in Jatía, Oriente, by José Martí and General Máximo Gómez addressed to the chiefs and officers of the town of Jiguaní. The document states that it had come to their attention that cattle was allowed to get through to the enemy supposedly by order of general Jesús Rabí. Since giving aid to the enemy in time of war was considered an act of treason they were sure that general Rabí had not given such order. Therefore, they prohibited the passage of cattle and other provisions through enemy lines and ordered that anyone making such request and presenting an order from general Rabí allowing them to get across enemy lines, be apprehended immediately and brought to general Rabí for questioning and trial	Jatía is a place located in the province of Granma. Ana Quesada letter to a general of Cuba's war of independence, July 24, 1899		Quesada, Ana		Letter dated in Savoie, France from Ana Quesada, widow of Carlos Manuel de Céspedes, to a general of Cuba's War of Independence, in which she complains about having received only a few lines from him although she has written several letters. She comments on the thermal baths of the hotel where she is staying and that she is following the indications of the doctor. She says that she feels very sad far away from Cuba and that in Europe nobody comments about the unfortunate island. She also sends greetings to the general's family and hopes that they finally have the consolation of being together. Samuel Thompson letter to his wife, June 20, 1898		Thompson, Samuel		Letter dated aboard the U.S. ship  Abarenda anchored in Guantánamo Harbor during the Spanish-American War, where Samuel Thompson describes to his wife the war's activities. He has the impression that the war will be over soon since the Spaniards are in a state of starvation. Affidavit notarized by Federico Castellanos Arteaga, June 21, 1901		Castellanos Arteaga, Federico		Affidavit notarized by Federico Castellanos Arteaga, notary public of the city of Puerto Príncipe, by which Pedro Nolasco Valdés Machado, an American citizen, accompanied by several witnesses declared that he was in the cattle business prior to the War of Independence, but that during the war the Spanish troops took over his property and as a consequence he lost everything he had. Being an American citizen he had to remain neutral during the war. The date has been taken from page 14 of the manuscript.		Valdés Machado, Pedro Nolasco; Legal documents; Notaries	Affidavits		1901-06-22	1900-1910	Camagüey (Cuba)	1 affidavit, 20 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Cuban Heritage Collection. Manuscript related to the bail assigned in the trial against Guillermo Moncada and others for rebellion, 1894				Manuscript related to the trial for rebellion against Guillermo Moncada, alias Guillermón, Victoriano Garzón, Juan Araujo Villasona, Agustín Araujo Villasona, Pedro Beaupliller, Doroteo Guilarte, Dionisio Bavastro, Crescencio del Toro, Tomás Muñoz, and Pedro A. Pérez. Provisional prison was given to the accused until each of the them paid a bail of 10,000 "pesetas". The signature of each of the accused appears acknowledging the judgment. Later, Pedro Pérez y González was set free because the authorities had confused him erroneously with Pedro A. Pérez		Moncada, Guillermón, 1841-1895; Garzón, Victoriano; Araujo Villasona, Juan; Araujo Villasona, Agustín; Beaupliller, Pedro; Guilarte, Doroteo; Bavastro, Dionisio; Toro, Crescencio del; Muñoz, Tomás; Pérez, Pedro A.; Bail; Cuba -- History -- 1878-1895; Spain -- Colonies -- Cuba	Manuscripts; Documents		1894	1890-1900	Baracoa (Cuba)	1 manuscript, 76 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Account of the escape of general John Cabell Breckinridge from Richmond to Cuba, 1865		Breckinridge, John C. (John Cabell), 1821-1875		Account of the escape of general Breckinridge from Richmond to the Island of Cuba in 1865, written from his own recollection of the events. After Richmond's surrender in April 1865, during the American Civil War, the Secretary of War, General John Cabell Breckinridge commanded the troops that accompanied Jefferson Davis, President of the Confederate States, and his cabinet. Davis was captured but Breckinridge evaded arrest and imprisonment by fleeing with a group of his men through the South and finally to Florida and Cuba. After remaining a few days in Cuba he traveled to England		Breckinridge, John C. (John Cabell), 1821-1875; Davis, Jefferson, 1808-1889; United States -- History -- Civil War, 1861-1865; Cuba	Manuscripts; Documents;		1865	1860-1870		1 manuscript, 48 pages	eng		University of Miami Libraries. Aragón, Cuban consul in Boston, Massachusetts, dated in Havana, about the Cuban food products with a greater possibility of being sold in New England and the specifications that they must fulfill. Samuel Thompson letter to his wife, June 12, 1898		Thompson, Samuel		Letter, dated in Guantánamo Bay during the Spanish-American War, from Samuel Thompson, chief engineer of the U.S. ship Abarenda. He comments to his wife that four US soldiers were killed early that morning. He also mentions that some of the men planted the first American flag on Cuban soil and that they will be using the guns during the night but that she should not worry about him. Sentencia pronunciada por el Sor D. Francisco Noval y Martí sobre nulidad de testamento	Sentence pronounced by Judge Francisco Noval y Martí on nullity of testament	Noval y Martí, Francisco		This sentence denies the demand presented by Francisca Cairo, mother of the minor Nicolás Serapio Gómez, against Olalla Cacho Negrete, widow of Nicolás José Gómez and executrix of his estate. Francisca Cairo had contested the validity of the will, dated December 14, 1889, on the grounds of Gómez's citizenship. She was demanding the rightful inheritance due to her son who was the grandson of Nicolás José Gómez.		Gómez, Nicolás José; Cairo, Francisca; Cacho Negrete, Olalla; Gómez, Nicolás Serapio; Justice, Administration of -- Cuba; Judges -- Cuba; Legal documents; Manuscripts; Wills	Manuscripts		1892-02-22	1890-1900	Havana (Cuba)	1 manuscript, 66 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Cuban Heritage Collection. Copia de la Escritura No. 81 de Arrendamiento del Hotel Nacional de Cuba	Copy of lease contract No. 81 of Hotel Nacional de Cuba	De Céspedes y Ortiz, Carlos Miguel; Brownson, Leonard E.		Carlos Miguel de Céspedes, Secretary of Public Works, representing the Cuban Government, and Leonard E. Browson as proxy of  the "Sociedad del Hotel Nacional de Cuba", appeared before Regino Truffin y Pérez de Abreu, lawyer and notary, to sign the agreement by which the Cuban government leased the area occupied by the old Santa Clara battery and adjacent areas, for the construction of the Hotel Nacional. The document establishes all pertinent regulations regarding the lease agreement.	Bound manuscript with a hardcover. Collection of fables written by Pedro Santacilia, June 1883				Fables were transcribed by a Mexican street scribe. Pedro Santacilia was a Cuban poet resident of Mexico City and married to Manuela Juárez Maza, Benito Juarez' daughter.		Santacilia, Pedro, 1826-1910; Fables	Manuscripts		1883-06	1880-1890	Mexico City (Mexico)	1 manuscript, 134 pages	spa		University of Miami Libraries. Cuban Heritage Collection. Wilfredo Paredes diary, c.1993		Paredes, Wilfredo		Wilfredo Paredes describes the years he spent jailed in Cuba and his struggle to escape from the island in search of freedom in the United States.	Translation in English is included.
